Notebook[{
Cell["Coordinatization", "Title",ExpressionUUID->"bad13323-7dcd-4429-bc89-35c1f619b9f3"],

Cell["\<\
The coordinatization layer is the synthetic-to-analytic bridge: it assigns to \
every vertex of a graph a coordinate tuple computed entirely from graph \
properties. Two coordinate systems are exposed -- spatial radar coordinates \
(resolving sets) and orthogonal coordinates (shortest-path projection onto \
axes). Together with FindOrthogonalFrame for axis discovery, the layer turns a \
synthetic graph into something downstream layers (tropical, projective, \
embedding-based finders) can consume.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"c066c617-37cd-41a5-aea5-2d3704ad6441"],

Cell["Setup", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"d20ae168-31c8-40ca-9d80-ccb73666f6f5"],

Cell["Load the paclet.", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"f8ac3b5a-6fc0-4580-b215-30392ef7c329"],

Cell["Needs[\"WolframInstitute`SyntheticInfrageometry`\"]", "Code",ExpressionUUID->"e9ac9118-3326-469c-9f26-74cf4ad465a3"],

Cell["Spatial radar coordinates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"64e62596-adc2-462b-8f66-fcd0ca16cba6"],

Cell["\<\
A radar basis is a vertex set B such that the distance map v |-> (d(v, b))_{b \
in B} is injective: every vertex is uniquely determined by its distance \
vector to B. Equivalently a resolving set. The size of a smallest radar basis \
is the metric dimension of the graph.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f1bf29b4-5746-4f08-891d-3804499ace6c"],

Cell["\<\
FindRadarBasis -- enumerate radar bases by ascending size; up to n bases via \
FindRadarBasis[graph, n].\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"518d9898-35f0-481f-9b60-4832ade3600e"],

Cell["\<\
RadarBasisQ -- test whether a vertex set resolves the graph (predicate \
companion of FindRadarBasis).\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"9339b575-0e63-451c-86e2-24833623868a"],

Cell["\<\
RadarCoordinates -- single-vertex form RadarCoordinates[graph, basis, v] \
returns the distance vector; bulk form RadarCoordinates[graph, basis] returns \
the Association of all vertices' coordinates, so RadarCoordinates[graph, basis][v] \
is the natural operator form.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"a851fc8f-6acb-413d-85c9-0d9915a59d2f"],

Cell["Orthogonal coordinates", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"a616b21f-d1f8-4e47-9e88-00b5a46fa467"],

Cell["\<\
Generalize Cartesian coordinates: pick n axes (each a vertex list line or a \
directed acyclic graph) and project each vertex onto every axis by \
shortest-path distance. The i-th coordinate is the layer index of v's \
projection onto the i-th axis.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e2555061-d3ab-426a-99b3-b956cc67c4b1"],

Cell["\<\
OrthogonalCoordinates[graph, {axis1, axis2, ...}, v] -- the n-tuple of layer \
indices for v.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"ef31b8a4-570b-417d-91e9-e3ac13fdef03"],

Cell["\<\
OrthogonalCoordinates[graph, axes] -- the Association of n-tuples for every \
vertex.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"26e01d88-0821-4733-bceb-8fd4508d1d4b"],

Cell["\<\
OrthogonalCoordinates[graph, c, v] -- auto-discovers orthogonal axes through \
center c via FindOrthogonalFrame and returns the Z-valued signed displacement \
of v from c. The bare two-argument form OrthogonalCoordinates[graph, c] \
returns the Association for every vertex with c at the origin {0, 0, ..., 0}.\
\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"7e001e0a-250c-445c-949c-554080fdf462"],

Cell["\<\
OrthogonalCoordinates[graph, InfraPoint[{v1, ..., vk}], v] -- multi-vertex \
center: each axis must contain at least one of the listed vertices as an \
interior point; signing uses the first listed vertex lying on each axis.\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"bc1d4111-bea1-4bd8-bcd6-ff3ad385a53f"],

Cell["Tied projections (Aggregation option)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"600033f3-19e0-4e0a-9cdf-9005e6e69545"],

Cell["\<\
Several axis vertices can be tied for closest to v -- e.g. on an even cycle, \
the antipode of an axis vertex sees two equally-distant axis points. The \
\"Aggregation\" option chooses how to reduce the list of tied layer indices \
to a single coordinate: \"First\" (default), \"Last\", \"Min\", \"Max\", \
\"Mean\", or \"Median\". On line axes \"First\" coincides with \"Min\" and \
\"Last\" with \"Max\"; on DAG axes they can differ.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"122e933c-1f0e-43cb-9cfa-78134efa7105"],

Cell["Orthogonal axes", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"b9eda318-e200-4610-9ed1-3337ecfabb0e"],

Cell["\<\
FindOrthogonalFrame[graph, n] returns n mutually well-separated longest paths \
in the graph (or $Failed if fewer exist); UpTo[n] is soft, All returns every \
axis above the separation threshold. The selection is greedy: start from one \
longest path; at each step pick the candidate path with maximum separation \
from the already-chosen axes; stop when separation drops below \
\"MinSeparation\".\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"5fa99789-0e41-440c-95a4-c4d53bc3b11e"],

Cell["\<\
FindOrthogonalFrame[graph, c, n] constrains every axis to pass through vertex \
c as an interior point, anchoring a sign convention for downstream Z-valued \
coordinates.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"2f968a85-6aee-4dbf-8cfe-81211f1d4178"],

Cell["\<\
FindOrthogonalFrame[graph, InfraPoint[{v1, ..., vk}], n] requires every axis \
to contain at least one of the listed vertices as an interior point.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"7ae03f3d-af4e-4876-9085-652600fb1cea"],

Cell["\<\
Options: \"AxisDistance\" (\"MinEndpoint\" | \"Hausdorff\" | \"Separation\") \
-- the pairwise axis distance used for separation; \"MinLength\" (Automatic = \
diameter); \"MinSeparation\" (Automatic = half axis length); \
\"AxisThickness\" (axes within this Hausdorff distance are kept together); \
\"RandomPick\" (False = first match deterministically).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"8cdc96d1-398b-40f7-8645-98c1bcea40c7"],

Cell["\<\
The number of axes through a point is itself a graph invariant -- the \
coordinatized dimension at c, computed as Length @ FindOrthogonalFrame[g, c, \
All] (no dedicated symbol, mirroring the radar-basis convention).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"04aec439-6304-40ad-9426-95a6cacfa0fe"],

Cell["Examples", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"005ad2af-adc6-48e6-a9e6-6d8e7635d137"],

Cell["\<\
A radar basis of the cycle C_6: any two non-antipodal vertices resolve every \
position.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"2a99a5c9-a0a5-4419-8065-3c2ae2e2e640"],

Cell["FindRadarBasis[CycleGraph[6]]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"f5381040-d29c-4bcc-ab41-ad56d2264f9b"],

Cell["\<\
Radar coordinates of every vertex of P_5 with respect to its endpoints.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"18dd9163-0574-47b4-ab94-e49ba2e56582"],

Cell["RadarCoordinates[PathGraph[Range[5]], {1, 5}]", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"fb408fe8-6df3-4c45-9ae9-0d87113d8d64"],

Cell["\<\
Cartesian coordinates on a 4 x 4 grid via the bottom row and left column as \
axes.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"839719aa-a0b6-4470-95f6-a88c3ad5b542"],

Cell["\<\
With[{g = GridGraph[{4, 4}], xAxis = {1, 2, 3, 4}, yAxis = {1, 5, 9, 13}}, \
OrthogonalCoordinates[g, {xAxis, yAxis}]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"cbc42acf-8729-42a3-9d7d-7372b073eb16"],

Cell["\<\
The same coordinates with the corner as origin -- now Z-valued.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"2022523f-57e2-4d47-805a-88fff9aa9cf2"],

Cell["\<\
OrthogonalCoordinates[GridGraph[{4, 4}], {{1, 2, 3, 4}, {1, 5, 9, 13}}, 11, \
\"Origin\" -> 1]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"9b9473d1-c079-4e2d-80d5-5226224f2a2f"],

Cell["\<\
Tied projection on the four-cycle: vertex 4 has distance 1 to both 1 and 3 on \
the axis {1, 2, 3}. Different aggregations give different coordinates.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"14984ff8-29d6-4a63-bc0b-de0889745982"],

Cell["\<\
With[{g = CycleGraph[4], axis = {{1, 2, 3}}}, Table[mode -> \
OrthogonalCoordinates[g, axis, 4, \"Aggregation\" -> mode], {mode, \
{\"First\", \"Last\", \"Mean\", \"Median\"}}]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"bdc20091-8c6b-4955-b1c6-3cc2aa6367cc"],

Cell["\<\
Orthogonal axes through a corner of a 5 x 5 grid (visualized).\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"5076c5fb-f7a1-4653-a914-5b8ee0bdfcac"],

Cell["\<\
With[{g = GridGraph[{5, 5}], c = 1}, InfraSceneHighlight[g, \
{InfraSegment[FindOrthogonalFrame[g, c, All]] -> Red, InfraPoint[{c}] -> \
Green}]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"ef746166-69e1-424e-852b-df29a727002b"],

Cell["\<\
Multi-vertex InfraPoint center: each axis passes through at least one listed \
vertex.\
\>", "CodeText",ExpressionUUID->"10ebf4ee-f030-479a-bfb2-80ca6e73ee07"],

Cell["\<\
With[{g = GridGraph[{5, 5}], anchors = {7, 19}}, InfraSceneHighlight[g, \
{InfraSegment[FindOrthogonalFrame[g, InfraPoint[anchors], All]] -> Red, \
InfraPoint[anchors] -> Green}]]\
\>", "Input",ExpressionUUID->"0f84a4f2-7f37-4a14-b784-4f3af3ac280b"],

Cell["Synthetic-to-analytic", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"1bf82dc7-45a3-4426-9c47-115055bd758e"],

Cell["\<\
The coordinatization layer is what makes graph-derived geometric algebra \
possible: every downstream calculation that wants to talk about coordinates \
-- tropical convexity, projective affinization, embedding-based finders -- \
consumes one of these tuples. Radar coordinates are intrinsic and always \
defined (modulo the existence of a resolving set, guaranteed by the n-1 \
leaves bound on trees); orthogonal coordinates require a choice of axes but \
recover the standard Cartesian system on flat substrates.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f9c3fb31-7a10-421e-9ced-9cc7fa689724"],

Cell["See also", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"21e5d279-a21f-411b-820e-833964d4df24"],

Cell["FindRadarBasis", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"b45dfc2f-3973-4956-8398-ae2b31a8fab5"],

Cell["RadarBasisQ", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"810b84df-a16c-4554-b9a6-ae6a5789cb4e"],

Cell["RadarCoordinates", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"6f29e87d-a47f-48a3-8c4f-2061451b79ab"],

Cell["OrthogonalCoordinates", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"dcc352ed-7b6f-4756-9e76-d8acaf86ce19"],

Cell["FindOrthogonalFrame", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"82f09e5e-fb8b-4c4d-81b2-389e547897af"],

Cell["MetricAlgebraGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"82b713d8-6727-4d80-af03-a85cb822113a"],

Cell["EuclideanGeometryGuide", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"147ec7be-eda7-4b9a-b501-2a3a68f13344"],

Cell["References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"7f34b2ac-a72f-45d6-8c8c-fef9dabe50d0"],

Cell["\<\
Chartrand, Eroh, Johnson, Oellermann, Resolvability in graphs and the metric \
dimension of a graph, Discrete Applied Mathematics 105, 2000\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"eb64bf41-ac82-494c-9631-905251c575d9"],

Cell["\<\
Slater, Leaves of trees, Congressus Numerantium 14, 1975 (origin of resolving \
sets)\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"d1114050-6ebc-40a9-95f4-e833b7a77061"],

Cell["\<\
Linial, Geodesic Geometry on Graphs, \
https://www.cs.huji.ac.il/~nati/PAPERS/ge_ge_gr.pdf\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"08839520-16c0-459d-a815-2a5e40a077a9"],

Cell["\<\
Foucaud, Mertzios, Naserasr, Parreau, Valicov, Identification, \
location-domination and metric dimension on interval and permutation graphs, \
Algorithmica 78, 2017\
\>", "Item",ExpressionUUID->"fa008449-5aa8-42fe-89ad-efc87a2d80a4"]
},
